I have a permanent art show in southern Utah. It’s very exclusive since you have to be friends with my parents to gain entry (since it’s in their house). 😆 

This piece is the newest addition to their collection. I worked off a picture my dad took and their only request was to use vibrant colors. It was a fun challenge to work outside my comfort zone in both color scheme and scale. 

I set up in their entryway on a card table and painted over Thanksgiving break. In a way it was like setting up a puzzle and slowly chipping away while visiting with family. Except way more fun. 😉

She is a lousy hide-and-go-seek partner, leaving tufts of white hair wherever she goes.  Louise is a close cuddler who believes that lying on your chest is endearing.  Sleep for Louise always follows a snort Steve Urkel could be proud of.  Together they love to play fetch and chase our kids around the house. Can you see the difference? 

I compared my kids’ cheap watercolor set with @m.grahamco professional paints and had to share the results.

Cheap Paint:
Didn’t have a very good flow, resulting in a more brush strokes
The color was less vibrant
Chalky finish
It was hard to get the paint to blend and bleed together

Professional:
The paints were so pigmented I only needed a small amount
Easier to mix to get the colors I wanted
The darks were easy to achieve without it feeling cakey
Paint consistency felt like honey

Although the professional paint is more expensive, the paint goes way farther so it may end up costing less in the long run. 

The painting experience will be more enjoyable with the high quality paint and you will be much happier with the outcome.

Are you struggling to get a good scan of your art? 

On today’s Tuesday tips I’ll share one simple fix that could make your scans go from this to this.

Tuesday Tips: Get the most out of your watercolor paints. 🎨

Tubes of professional watercolor paints may seem expensive, but with a few tricks they can last forever!

1. Fill the deep end of the well with paint. This gives you room on the shallow side to get the right consistency. The runoff will be saved for later and you’ll waste less when rinsing your brush.

2. Don’t use freshly squeezed paint! There’s no rule against it, but I’ve found if I dive right into gooey, highly pigmented paint, my brush grabs too much and I end up rinsing my brush more. If you let it dry and reactivate with water, it’s easier to have more control over the amount of paint on your brush and use less in the long run.

3. Keep a spray bottle nearby. I just recently added a spray bottle to my studio and I’m shocked at the difference it’s made. I can quickly clean off the mixing areas on my palette, reactivate my paint, and get right to work. It’s also been a lifesaver when I’ve had paint drip and need some clean water for a quick cleanup.

4. Store paint tubes in a lipstick organizer. Not only is it pretty, but has helped me from buying duplicates I didn’t realize I already had. 😄

Tuesday Tips: Paint a Dog in Six Steps

1. Mask and define: I start by defining the lightest and darkest areas on my portrait. I use masking fluid on the highlights and deep colors to map out the darkest details. I don’t see a lot of other artists using this method, but it works well for me.

2. Mid tones: I paint loose, watery washes for the midtones, finishing off the first layer.

3. Build contrast: I add more lights and darks within each section by removing masking fluid, scrubbing back color and adding darker details. 

4. Soften: After I add details, I go back over my brushstrokes with either a wash or damp brush to soften out the painting.

5. Repeat: It may seem like I wasted time softening those detailed lines, but the purpose is to build depth and texture. I add details again and this time I paint small highlights with white ink. 

6. Final wash: After the ink is completely dry, I soften the bright white with a gentle wash to avoid reactivating the ink.

My watercolor fur process:

1. Line. Even though this layer will be blurred as I build up layers, this first step helps me block out colors and texture. Make sure you don’t use hard outlines, but follow the movement of individual hairs. I like to use my 10/0 Liner velvetouch brush.

2. Wet on wet washes. This is the part everyone loves! I paint right over my first sketchy layer and let the colors blend and bleed together. Make sure to keep your brush loaded with watery paint. Depending on the size of the wash, I like to either use my size 4 round velvetouch, or size 8 Long Round Aqua Elite brush.

3. Layer fine lines. After the painting has its first full layer down, I start to build up texture and contrast gradually with my liner brush.

4. Soften lines. Using a damp, size 4 round rush, I gently soften the detailed lines. If I need to adjust the color or value, I’ll use a light wash to soften the first layers.

5. Repeat. Fur texture works best when I build up layers gradually. I repeat the steps above to build depth.

6. White ink highlights. Using my liner or round 20/0 mini-detailer brush, I carefully add white ink highlights. Be careful not to go overboard as the ink is opaque and can overwhelm the more transparent watercolor.

7. Soften whites. After the ink has dried I float a wash over the ink to soften the bright white. If needed, I’ll lift some of the ink with a damp brush and paper towel.

8. Adjust values. At the end of the painting I check the overall values and try to look at the painting as a whole. Sometimes I get so lost in the details I forget about the big picture. I darken areas with washes, add contrast with detail, and lift paint in areas with a light wash of water and a paper towel.

I hope this was helpful! Please let me know if you have any questions about my fur painting process.
